    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-09-03T11:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-09-03T11:00:00-05:00" n="233"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d233">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72112Sa/122</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_PWH1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Page</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-09-03T17:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">September 3, 1918—5 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 5.30 p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1589. My 1456, August 28, 10 [<hi rend="italic">11</hi>] p.m. It has now been
                    decided, as the best course to follow in view of the recent publication of the
                    French decree in regard to the so-called German safe conducts and the objections
                    of some of the Entente ministers in Denmark and <pb facs="0269" n="1103"
                        xml:id="pg_1103"/> Holland to a formal identic communication, to instruct
                    the Allied ministers at Stockholm simultaneously to present, <hi rend="italic"
                        >mutatis mutandis</hi>, the note reported in my telegram above referred to,
                    but to leave the choice to the ministers in the other neutral countries of the
                    form in which the communication is to be made, i. e., whether it is to be formal
                    or informal; the wording to be the same in all countries, omitting, of course,
                    the statement in the second paragraph intended only for Sweden. In the case of
                    Spain it is deemed wiser to leave to the chiefs of mission the choice, as well,
                    of time of presentation, in order that they may select a propitious moment. It
                    was decided that no publicity should be given to the form or purport of the
                    communications. It is hoped that you will concur in this course and instruct our
                    representatives accordingly.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_PWH1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Page</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
